text: Dean I'm listening to the latest Commander Time and regarding your description of combo decks, I think your definition of 'fair' is different than mine.  :sunglasses:
Lolol
The no turns episode?
Nope - threat assessment.
Dean described combo decks as fair.
Which I assume he really means indiscriminate.

For me a lot of it depends on the player/deck. We've got a kid in our group who plays exclusively combo, his two primary decks being Prossh and Azami. But both are relatively slow-roll combo he isn't tutoring for and require a ton of moving pieces. His Azami deck wins with some kind of Labman finish off Thought Reflection and High Tide with Azami out, and Prossh has typical Prossh stuff, but he isn't tutoring for pieces so you can always see it coming. It's never annoying to lose to him because you always feel like you had ample time to respond. He also is a really nice, funny guy with a great attitude who is always great to play with.

Conversely there's this other guy who plays maybe once a month due to his work schedule who I avoid like the plague. He plays exclusively Flash/Hulk insta-win type stuff, and he couples that with being the most smug guy on the planet. He does this thing where he plays his obvious combo then looks around at every person at the table to make sure you're acknowledging how clever he was to Flash in a Protean Hulk. It's the most punchable thing ever.
I hate those types of plebs
"Here's this deck I came up with all on my own! I didn't use edhrec or any other resources because I'm such a great deck builder!"
"I also host a podcast with my brother..."
lol
That was mean.
I'm just grumpy because it's finally less than a billion degrees outside and I'm working all day

<@U4V5EHQ2G> agreed that it's dependent on players/deck. My group has mostly been friends at school, very very small. Mostly lower powered because a lot of the guys are new. The older of the players is a bit of a spike and just runs out his combo quickly. Unfortunately, because of the newness, I basically have to play to police his deck because else-wise we just lose to the most forecasted combo ever. Combine with the braggadocios attitude he had it got tiresome and I stopped playing for a long time.
Speaking of grumpy, I've noticed for myself I'm radically less likely to get annoyed at someone if I ate before a  long game night. Low bloodsugar and being easily annoyed is a thing, at least for me
The diabetus got you down?
The shug as some would call it?
It's kinda become a joke where we play where if someone is acting pissy we always ask when they ate last and the answer is always like six hours ago.
That's correct
<@U3FV90TCZ> Playing police is never fun
Particularly when you're doing it so other people can have a good game

Yup. The winning balanced out, but having to hold up removal for 2 turns for the KikiJiki/Crafter combo never feels good because the newer players didn't understand it.
This was a few years ago and really burnt me out of EDH for a long time.
That's something I think would be a good topic for you guys to cover eventually, how people playing obnoxiously can burn others out and turn them off to the game/format
Or just "People are the worst, so don't be a dick"
I'd like to do an etiquette episode
It does seem to be lacking in the broad spectrum of playing with strangers, and you guys all have a good grip on it
I'm surprised none of you are giving me shit about the BSB Patreon hitting $1k today
I already tweeted about
can I have some of that money Jason? I promise that I won't waste it on anything except magic cards
also, anyone going to be at GP Minneapolis beside me?
<@U32LRG9NU> is the king of shameless self promotion. This just solidifies that notion
I'm actually not really happy about what happened
We got basically 0 new patrons. Existing patrons increased their pledges which means they'll likely drop them back down next month
ahhhh
It's disappointing, but that's to be expected with a gimmick
Yea, reading the discord chat I agree with that. Most of those people are only going to do it for the initial perks and then drop. I think that's how most patreon's would go though
I like the spreadsheet idea to as a lasting perk to keep people at a certain level.
That's why stuff like glasses and playmats work better for a Kickstarter than a Patreon
But we didn't have many ideas
For sure. It's hard to get creative with lasting value type items people will stick around for
I think at $1.5k we will do a Q&A or something
GP meetups for patrons?
It's not like Corbin isn't there to not acknowledge people
Hahaha "no, I will not acknowledge anyone at a gp without verifying they are a patron"
That's what I do
"Ah, only. 1 dollar patron, you get a "hello"
I got a "Hey man, what not playing merfolk?" from Corbin at GP Louisville. I think that might be a record for him
$1 Patrons get access to the Discord server which should be a $5 perk
Probably.

Making people earn for the lowest hanging fruit and throwing out incentives to not just do the basic $1 isn't a new concept. I think at some point you guys definitely could change it to being a $5 perk and just tell people "you know the value of the chat so you know it's still worth it"
And most people wouldn't blink at it
